1.3 Using Gradient Descent to fit¶

(1) the sigmoid function¶

In [224]:
def sigmoid(theta, x_vector):
    z = np.dot(theta.transpose(), x_vector)
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))

In [334]:
# Note:
# As you can see, we are calculating derivative of each parameter theta(j)
# but for the simplicity of coding below, we consider theta as a vector
# this does not affect the formula

# my comment of the formula if you feel hard to understand:
# 1. it is easy to understand the basic format, update with learning rate * gradient

# 2. take a look at the gradient we can see that it contains two parts
# one part is the "error" between the true_label and the predicted_label
# another part is the corresponding x(j)
# consider z = x(1)*theta(1) + x(2)*theta(2) + ... + x(j)*theta(j) is a linear function
# thus according to the chain rule, the derivative must contain a corresponding x(j)

# 3. if we consider all the thetas as a vector, it is still this formula
# just ignore (j) and update as a vector, like this:

# for each row in the dataset:
#     calculate the "error" (a number), i.e. the true label - predicted probability
#     multiply the row (a vector) with this number
#     sum up all these rows, e.g., [1, 2, -1] + [0, 1, 1] = [1, 3, 0] ...
#     return sum
# new_theta = old_theta + learning_rate * sum (a vector)

(7) coding¶

In [315]:
def gradient_descent(x, y, theta, learning_rate = 0.01, iterations = 1000):  
   
    for it in range(iterations):
        
        loss = np.zeros(x.shape[1])
        
        # we use the most basic method which takes all the observations
        for i in range(0, x.shape[0]):

            predicted_label = sigmoid(theta, x[i])
            true_label = y[i]
            error = (true_label - predicted_label) * x[i]
            loss = loss + error
    
        # setting lambda as large as 5 to reduce overfitting
        # average by "1/x.shape[0]" to make the process smooth, i.e. a little step each time
        
        # you don't have to set lambda this large
        # you don't have to divide by N (the number of rows)
        # so basically you can just use "theta + learning_rate  * (loss - 5 * theta)"
        # this is just for better accuracy
        
        theta = theta + 1/x.shape[0] * learning_rate  * (loss - 5 * theta)

    return theta

# final notes:
# the dataset used in this example is extremely small (150 rows and 5 columns)
# so it is common that if you set lambda small (1 or 2), or with a high learning rate (0.1)
# or few iterations (under 1000)
# you may not get a result close to the coefficient fit by sklearn
